<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"><h2 id="meiosis-source-of-genetic-variation">Meiosis: Source of Genetic Variation</h2><ul><li><p>Meiosis gives rise to cells that are <b>genetically different </b>from each other and is the type of cell division used to produce <b>gametes</b> (sex cells)</p></li><li><p>During meiosis, the nucleus of the original 'parent' cell undergoes <b>two rounds of division</b>. These are:</p><ul><li><p><b>Meiosis I</b></p></li><li><p><b>Meiosis II</b></p></li></ul></li></ul><p><b>Meiosis I</b></p><ul><li><p>The nucleus of the original 'parent' cell is <b>diploid</b> (2n) i.e. it contains <b>two sets of chromosomes</b></p></li><li><p>Before meiosis I, these chromosomes <b>replicate</b></p></li><li><p>During meiosis I, the homologous pairs of chromosomes are split up, to produce two <b>haploid</b> (n) nuclei</p><ul><li><p>At this point, each chromosome still consists of <b>two chromatids</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>Note that the chromosome number halves (from 2n to n) in the <b>first division</b> of meiosis (<b>meiosis I</b>), not the second division (meiosis II)</p></li></ul><h4 id="meiosis-ii">Meiosis II</h4><ul><li><p>During meiosis II, the chromatids that make up each chromosome separate to produce <b>four</b> <b>haploid</b> (n) nuclei</p><ul><li><p>At this point, each chromosome now consists of a <b>single chromatid</b></p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Meiosis I and II" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="746" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Meiosis-I-and-II.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Meiosis-I-and-II.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>During meiosis, one diploid nucleus divides by meiosis to produce four haploid nuclei</b></i></p><ul><li><p>Having <b>genetically different offspring </b>can be <b>advantageous</b> for <b>natural selection</b></p></li><li><p>Meiosis has several mechanisms that<b> increase the genetic diversity of gametes </b>produced</p></li><li><p>Both <b>crossing over</b> and<b> independent assortment</b> result in <b>different combinations of alleles</b> in gametes</p></li></ul><h4 id="crossing-over">Crossing over</h4><ul><li><p>Crossing over is the process by which <b>non-sister chromatids exchange alleles</b></p></li><li><p>Process:</p><ul><li><p>During <b>meiosis I</b> homologous chromosomes pair up and are in very close proximity to each other</p></li><li><p>The paired chromosomes are known as <b>bivalents</b></p></li><li><p>The non-sister chromatids can <b>cross over</b> and get entangled</p></li><li><p>These crossing points are called <b>chiasmata</b></p></li><li><p>The entanglement places stress on the DNA molecules</p></li><li><p>As a result of this, a section of chromatid from one chromosome may <b>break</b> and <b>rejoin</b> with the chromatid from the <b>other chromosome</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>This <b>swapping of alleles</b> is significant as it can result in a <b>new combination of alleles on the two chromosomes</b></p></li><li><p>There is usually at least one, if not more, chiasmata present in each <b>bivalent</b> during meiosis</p></li><li><p>Crossing over is more likely to occur further down the chromosome away from the centromere</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Genetic Variation Crossing Over" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="970" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Genetic-Variation-Crossing-Over.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Crossing over of non-sister chromatids leads to the exchange of genetic material</b></i></p><h4 id="independent-assortment">Independent assortment</h4><ul><li><p>Independent assortment is the production of <b>different combinations of alleles</b> in daughter cells due to the<b> random alignment of homologous pairs</b> along the equator of the spindle during <b>meiosis I</b></p></li><li><p>The different combinations of chromosomes in daughter cells increases genetic variation between gametes</p></li><li><p>In meiosis I, homologous chromosomes pair up and are pulled towards the equator of the spindle</p><ul><li><p>Each pair can be arranged with either chromosome on top, this is <b>completely random</b></p></li><li><p>The orientation of one homologous pair is <b>independent/unaffected</b> by the orientation of any other pair</p></li></ul></li><li><p>The homologous chromosomes are then separated and pulled apart to different poles</p></li><li><p>The combination of alleles that end up in each daughter cell depends on<b> how the pairs of homologous chromosomes were lined up</b></p></li><li><p>To work out the number of different possible chromosome combinations the formula 2<sup>n</sup> can be used, where n corresponds to the number of chromosomes in a haploid cell</p></li><li><p>For humans, this is 2<sup>23</sup> which calculates as 8,324,608 different combinations</p></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Independent assortment (1)" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="775" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Independent-assortment-1.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-1.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Independent assortment (2)" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="692" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Independent-assortment-2.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/03/Independent-assortment-2.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Independent assortment of homologous chromosomes leads to different genetic combinations in daughter cells</b></i></p></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="callout"><div class="ContentBlock_callout___oem_" data-variant="exam-tip"><header class="mb-3"><span class="ContentBlock_calloutIcon__XHWM5"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="Icon_icon__caLMg Icon_xl__PzZaA" focusable="false" height="24" viewbox="0 0 24 24" width="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M9 21c0 .5.4 1 1 1h4c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-1H9v1zm3-19C8.1 2 5 5.1 5 9c0 2.4 1.2 4.5 3 5.7V17c0 .5.4 1 1 1h6c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-2.3c1.8-1.3 3-3.4 3-5.7 0-3.9-3.1-7-7-7z"></path></svg></span><h4 class="h5">Examiner Tips and Tricks</h4></header><p>Several sources of genetic variation have been outlined above. It is also worth remembering that genetic variation can occur on an even smaller scale than chromosomes. <b>Mutations</b> can occur within genes. A random mutation that takes place during DNA replication can lead to the production of new alleles and increased genetic variation.</p></div></div></div></div>